1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,000
 Hi guys, good morning everybody. My name is Jackie and this is my youth mentor, Alson.

2
00:00:07,000 --> 00:00:14,000
 And today's scripture we're going to read from Matthew chapter 2, verse 3 to 8.

3
00:00:14,000 --> 00:00:22,000
 Now, when Jesus was born in Bethlehem of Judea in the days of Herod the king,

4
00:00:22,000 --> 00:00:28,000
 behold, there came wise men from the east to Jerusalem.

5
00:00:28,000 --> 00:00:37,000
 When Herod the king had heard these things, he was troubled, and all Jerusalem with him.

6
00:00:37,000 --> 00:00:44,000
 When king Herod heard this, he was disturbed, and all Jerusalem with him.

7
00:00:44,000 --> 00:00:52,000
 When he had called together all the people's chief priests and teachers of the law,

8
00:00:52,000 --> 00:00:56,000
 he asked them where the Messiah was to be born.

9
00:00:56,000 --> 00:01:07,000
 Then Herod called the Magi secretly and found out from them the exact time the star had appeared.

10
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:14,000
 He sent them to Bethlehem and said, "Go and search carefully for the child.

11
00:01:14,000 --> 00:01:25,000
 As soon as you find him, report to him so that I too may go and worship him."

12
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:29,000
 Now I will lead us to a prayer.

13
00:01:29,000 --> 00:01:40,000
 Lord, as we light this candle of hope and anticipation for the time when you will make all things right,

14
00:01:40,000 --> 00:01:47,000
 Lord, help us to make room in our hearts for what you have to say to us.

15
00:01:47,000 --> 00:01:52,000
 Thank you, Jesus. In the name of Jesus, I pray. Amen.

16
00:01:52,000 --> 00:01:54,000
 [Applause]

17
00:01:54,000 --> 00:02:04,000
 [Music]

18
00:02:05,000 --> 00:02:27,000
 [Music]

19
00:02:27,000 --> 00:02:34,000
 The first candle that is lit for Advent is a singular candle.

20
00:02:34,000 --> 00:02:40,000
 It's a small flame that flickers amongst great darkness.

21
00:02:40,000 --> 00:02:46,000
 And in many ways, that's very beautifully fitting for the Advent story itself.

22
00:02:46,000 --> 00:02:52,000
 You have in the one singular flame this idea of, I think, what the gospel is all about.

23
00:02:52,000 --> 00:03:05,000
 This subtle, quiet, and yet immovable power of God to break hope into an empire of darkness.

24
00:03:05,000 --> 00:03:11,000
 When you light a single candle in a dark room, it transforms that room.

25
00:03:11,000 --> 00:03:18,000
 Such a small thing bringing such hope within such largeness around it.

26
00:03:18,000 --> 00:03:26,000
 And in many ways, this is very fitting to how the gospel writers brings us the story of Jesus' birth.

27
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:32,000
 Unlike how I think we often think of it, or at least how we celebrate it in our modern era.

28
00:03:32,000 --> 00:03:35,000
 The gospel writers do not provide a huge amount of fanfare.

29
00:03:35,000 --> 00:03:42,000
 They're not providing like this great joy and this great light, smokes, and mirrors to celebrate the arrival of Jesus.

30
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:48,000
 In fact, the gospel writers present to us a pretty bleak picture.

31
00:03:48,000 --> 00:03:57,000
 They situate the arrival of the Messiah, of the one true King, right in the midst of all the darkness.

32
00:03:57,000 --> 00:04:02,000
 They show us, indeed, the need that the Jewish people had.

33
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:06,000
 That they were crying out for God to step in and liberate them.

34
00:04:06,000 --> 00:04:13,000
 Liberate them from the brutality of empire, from the grip of oppression,

35
00:04:13,000 --> 00:04:22,000
 and from perhaps the thing that can impact people the most, the abuse of human power.

36
00:04:22,000 --> 00:04:26,000
 This is how we come to see that gospel story.

37
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:32,000
 In fact, one of the most central stories or central moments of the Advent season

38
00:04:32,000 --> 00:04:38,000
 situates us in that idea of this great darkness around us.

39
00:04:38,000 --> 00:04:45,000
 Luke, when he's presenting the story, starts by explaining that a census is put out by Caesar Augustus

40
00:04:45,000 --> 00:04:47,000
 for the whole of the Roman Empire.

41
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:51,000
 History tells us that this took place in 6 BC.

42
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:57,000
 And it shows right away the kind of environment that the Jewish people were under at the time.

43
00:04:57,000 --> 00:05:00,000
 This census was incredibly disruptive.

44
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:05,000
 It meant that every citizen had to leave where it was that they were living at the time

45
00:05:05,000 --> 00:05:13,000
 and return back to where the male husband or the male leader or the oldest male of the family was from.

46
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:18,000
 And so the family would have to follow the male side and go to their hometown.

47
00:05:18,000 --> 00:05:23,000
 So this was already a sense of power in the Greek or Roman Empire.

48
00:05:23,000 --> 00:05:26,000
 Like, "We're going to make this census. We're going to make this decree.

49
00:05:26,000 --> 00:05:31,000
 And you, regardless of how you're feeling, are going to have to uproot yourself from where you are.

50
00:05:31,000 --> 00:05:38,000
 And you're going to have to return with your family back to your home place, the place that you yourself was born."

51
00:05:38,000 --> 00:05:43,000
 This is the backdrop to what causes Joseph and Mary to have to uproot themselves

52
00:05:43,000 --> 00:05:50,000
 from their safety of their home in Nazareth and travel the 145 kilometers south

53
00:05:50,000 --> 00:05:53,000
 down to his birthplace of Bethlehem.

54
00:05:53,000 --> 00:05:55,000
 That journey was long.

55
00:05:55,000 --> 00:05:57,000
 It was arduous. It was dangerous.

56
00:05:57,000 --> 00:06:04,000
 They actually had to go around Samaria because it was too dangerous to travel through Samaria itself.

57
00:06:04,000 --> 00:06:09,000
 And then add to the reality that Mary's doing this journey heavily pregnant.

58
00:06:09,000 --> 00:06:15,000
 And as you're reading this and as you're picking up the vibes that Luke is providing for us in the story,

59
00:06:15,000 --> 00:06:19,000
 that this is oppressive, number one, that this is dangerous, number two,

60
00:06:19,000 --> 00:06:22,000
 that poor Mary has to do this in the state that she's in,

61
00:06:22,000 --> 00:06:27,000
 you read it and you come to think, "Well, at least they're going to get to Bethlehem and everything's going to be okay."

62
00:06:27,000 --> 00:06:32,000
 Like, at least once they get there, they're going to be amongst Joseph's family.

63
00:06:32,000 --> 00:06:37,000
 That surely the relatives of Joseph in Bethlehem will open their doors and welcome them in

64
00:06:37,000 --> 00:06:40,000
 and everything will start to be okay.

65
00:06:40,000 --> 00:06:42,000
 And we know the story, don't we?

66
00:06:42,000 --> 00:06:45,000
 That Joseph and Mary arrive in Bethlehem after this long journey,

67
00:06:45,000 --> 00:06:52,000
 which would have taken about three weeks and nobody in Bethlehem opened their doors for them.

68
00:06:52,000 --> 00:07:02,000
 It was almost as if the relatives of Joseph wanted nothing to do with an unmarried pregnant girl.

69
00:07:02,000 --> 00:07:08,000
 And so they're forced to go into the only place where they could find shelter,

70
00:07:08,000 --> 00:07:11,000
 which were what we call a stable.

71
00:07:11,000 --> 00:07:12,000
 But I've actually been to Bethlehem.

72
00:07:12,000 --> 00:07:16,000
 If you go to Bethlehem these days, you can actually visit some of these places.

73
00:07:16,000 --> 00:07:20,000
 They were literally like caves under the homes at the time.

74
00:07:20,000 --> 00:07:26,000
 And you would go into those caves, and those caves would be where the animals were sheltered at nighttime.

75
00:07:26,000 --> 00:07:31,000
 And so Mary and Joseph are forced to go into that very place,

76
00:07:31,000 --> 00:07:40,000
 the place where we would think would be the last place that God might want the arrival of His Son.

77
00:07:40,000 --> 00:07:45,000
 One of my favorite paintings on this nativity scene is done by a painter called Edward Stott.

78
00:07:45,000 --> 00:07:47,000
 And he painted it in 1935.

79
00:07:47,000 --> 00:07:49,000
 Let me show you this painting.

80
00:07:49,000 --> 00:07:52,000
 This is one of my favorite paintings of the Christmas story.

81
00:07:52,000 --> 00:07:56,000
 But you might look at it and go, "Really, Andrew? That's a pretty boring painting."

82
00:07:56,000 --> 00:07:59,000
 Most of that painting is just dark.

83
00:07:59,000 --> 00:08:04,000
 But what I love about this painting is this is not the Hallmark Christmas card kind of Christmas

84
00:08:04,000 --> 00:08:07,000
 that I think we get used to in our modern time.

85
00:08:07,000 --> 00:08:11,000
 This is actually what it would have been like in the first century.

86
00:08:11,000 --> 00:08:15,000
 I mean, I want you to sit for a moment in the reality of the darkness that is here,

87
00:08:15,000 --> 00:08:19,000
 of the oppressive feel that this painting brings.

88
00:08:19,000 --> 00:08:24,000
 There are other figures in the painting, but you can't really see them very well.

89
00:08:24,000 --> 00:08:28,000
 It's dark, and it's gloomy, and it's damp, and it's lonely.

90
00:08:28,000 --> 00:08:32,000
 If you see the actual real painting, it's a lot darker than this reproduction.

91
00:08:32,000 --> 00:08:37,000
 But the painting is gloomy because that's what it was like in that moment.

92
00:08:37,000 --> 00:08:39,000
 And I love what Stott's done here in the painting.

93
00:08:39,000 --> 00:08:47,000
 He's only highlighted in the light two people, which happens to be Mary and her baby Jesus.

94
00:08:47,000 --> 00:08:50,000
 And it's almost like the painter is saying this.

95
00:08:50,000 --> 00:08:58,000
 There's this darkness and this gloom all around us, but there is a singular hope.

96
00:08:58,000 --> 00:09:05,000
 It's like he's trying to draw us into the very place that despite the reality of darkness in this world,

97
00:09:05,000 --> 00:09:10,000
 there has come one who can bring hope,

98
00:09:10,000 --> 00:09:15,000
 which is a very important message for us in our city this week

99
00:09:15,000 --> 00:09:22,000
 as we sit in the reality of the hurt and the pain and the brokenness of our world

100
00:09:22,000 --> 00:09:25,000
 very freshly for us here in Hong Kong.

101
00:09:25,000 --> 00:09:32,000
 We're drawn towards this one singular person of hope,

102
00:09:32,000 --> 00:09:42,000
 almost as if this painting is like a singular Advent candle lit on the first Sunday of the season,

103
00:09:42,000 --> 00:09:47,000
 bringing light to the darkness all around it.

104
00:09:47,000 --> 00:09:51,000
 I love the way that Luke actually opens up for us this very nativity scene.

105
00:09:51,000 --> 00:09:56,000
 Let me read this to you from Luke 2, verses 6 and 7.

106
00:09:56,000 --> 00:10:01,000
 He says, "While Mary and Joseph were still there in Bethlehem, the time came for the baby to be born.

107
00:10:01,000 --> 00:10:04,000
 And she gave birth to him, her firstborn son.

108
00:10:04,000 --> 00:10:12,000
 She wrapped him in a cloth and placed him in a manger because there was no room for them in the inn."

109
00:10:12,000 --> 00:10:15,000
 This phrase, "There was no room for them in the inn,"

110
00:10:15,000 --> 00:10:20,000
 has become perhaps the most central phrase in the whole of the Christmas story.

111
00:10:20,000 --> 00:10:23,000
 I mean, you ask any kid about Christmas and what they know of their story,

112
00:10:23,000 --> 00:10:28,000
 they'll probably tell you there was no room for Mary and Joseph, and they had to go to the stable.

113
00:10:28,000 --> 00:10:34,000
 And this idea of no room being in the inn becomes one of the most central points of the story

114
00:10:34,000 --> 00:10:37,000
 and one that should deeply challenge us.

115
00:10:37,000 --> 00:10:44,000
 I mean, again, put yourself in the dirty, dusty sandals of Joseph and Mary for a moment.

116
00:10:44,000 --> 00:10:49,000
 I mean, for Mary, I'm sure she had ideas of where she wanted her son to be born into the world,

117
00:10:49,000 --> 00:10:55,000
 but I'm sure she never would have chosen a dark, damp cave that stunk of animals.

118
00:10:55,000 --> 00:11:04,000
 Them being in that situation was a surprise to them, but note this, church, it was not a surprise to God.

119
00:11:04,000 --> 00:11:10,000
 In fact, if you step back for a moment, this actually opens up for us something really important.

120
00:11:10,000 --> 00:11:16,000
 That God ordained the birth of His Son, the birth of our Messiah,

121
00:11:16,000 --> 00:11:23,000
 the birth of the King of Kings, our eternal King, not in a palace adorned with beauty,

122
00:11:23,000 --> 00:11:26,000
 not an amazing home that was prepared for Him,

123
00:11:26,000 --> 00:11:31,000
 not from parents who were occupying the corridors of power at the time.

124
00:11:31,000 --> 00:11:40,000
 No, Jesus is born into the darkness of a stable, and God says that place is fit for a king.

125
00:11:40,000 --> 00:11:45,000
 Which is a beautiful thing, because right here at the beginning of the Advent story,

126
00:11:45,000 --> 00:11:49,000
 I think we get the whole of the gospel presented to us.

127
00:11:49,000 --> 00:11:54,000
 For if Jesus could be born into the darkness of a stable,

128
00:11:54,000 --> 00:11:59,000
 maybe He could also be born in the darkness of our hearts.

129
00:11:59,000 --> 00:12:08,000
 And that part of the gospel story sits true for all of us and welcomes us into it.

130
00:12:08,000 --> 00:12:13,000
 For Jesus has indeed come, and He's come to the darkness of a stable

131
00:12:13,000 --> 00:12:18,000
 to show us that there is no place where this King is not willing to associate Himself.

132
00:12:18,000 --> 00:12:22,000
 That there's no place where this King cannot step into the brokenness and the darkness

133
00:12:22,000 --> 00:12:30,000
 and the sin and the evil of this world and be made glorified.

134
00:12:30,000 --> 00:12:32,000
 Jesus has indeed come.

135
00:12:32,000 --> 00:12:39,000
 The question, though, is have we made room in our hearts to receive Him?

136
00:12:39,000 --> 00:12:46,000
 Or perhaps another way of saying it is, is there actually room in our inn?

137
00:12:46,000 --> 00:12:51,000
 Now, for us as Christians, we think about this primarily from the perspective of salvation.

138
00:12:51,000 --> 00:12:56,000
 That ultimately what we want is to open our hearts to a relationship with Jesus.

139
00:12:56,000 --> 00:13:00,000
 To recognize that He forgives sin, and in the midst of that, find salvation in our lives.

140
00:13:00,000 --> 00:13:04,000
 What a joy it is to know a Savior like that.

141
00:13:04,000 --> 00:13:09,000
 And absolutely, the Advent message and what Jesus would go on and do in His life,

142
00:13:09,000 --> 00:13:14,000
 death and resurrection, provides for us that beautiful idea that if we make space in our heart for Him,

143
00:13:14,000 --> 00:13:20,000
 we will come into eternal life in salvation with Him.

144
00:13:20,000 --> 00:13:25,000
 But I think there's something else at play here as well.

145
00:13:25,000 --> 00:13:29,000
 You see, I think this challenge that Advent brings us is not just a challenge for us Christians

146
00:13:29,000 --> 00:13:34,000
 about the place of salvation and that moment where we accept Jesus as our Savior.

147
00:13:34,000 --> 00:13:40,000
 It's also a challenge as to whether we are living out our discipleship with Him

148
00:13:40,000 --> 00:13:47,000
 in ways that enable more and more of Jesus to have kingship in our lives.

149
00:13:47,000 --> 00:13:51,000
 Our question, I think, as Christians, if you're a Christian here in this room,

150
00:13:51,000 --> 00:13:56,000
 is are you ongoing making room in your life for Jesus?

151
00:13:56,000 --> 00:14:04,000
 Are you making more and more room for the King to rule and to be who He wants to be in your life?

152
00:14:04,000 --> 00:14:08,000
 This is the very invitation of discipleship.

153
00:14:08,000 --> 00:14:13,000
 Discipleship is the very thing of saying there's still some stuff in my heart.

154
00:14:13,000 --> 00:14:16,000
 There's still some stuff in my thinking.

155
00:14:16,000 --> 00:14:20,000
 There's still some stuff in my flesh that is bound to sin that I want to deal with,

156
00:14:20,000 --> 00:14:23,000
 that I want to remove, that I want to release,

157
00:14:23,000 --> 00:14:29,000
 so that I can welcome in more of the reign of the kingdom of God in my life.

158
00:14:29,000 --> 00:14:33,000
 Here at the mine, our vision is growing big people.

159
00:14:33,000 --> 00:14:36,000
 It's a discipleship vision. We get it from Ephesians 4,

160
00:14:36,000 --> 00:14:38,000
 where Paul writes to the church and he says,

161
00:14:38,000 --> 00:14:42,000
 "Here's my prayer for you, that you would come to attain to the whole measure

162
00:14:42,000 --> 00:14:45,000
 of the wholeness of Christ, which challenges me.

163
00:14:45,000 --> 00:14:49,000
 Do I have the whole measure of the wholeness of Christ in me,

164
00:14:49,000 --> 00:15:00,000
 or is my inn so full of other things that Jesus is relegated to the stable of my life?"

165
00:15:00,000 --> 00:15:03,000
 It's a challenging thought.

166
00:15:03,000 --> 00:15:08,000
 But it's one that I think sobers us at a time like this in Advent.

167
00:15:08,000 --> 00:15:18,000
 What is it that I might need to remove from my life to be able to make room more for Jesus?

168
00:15:18,000 --> 00:15:25,000
 At Christmas time, could it be that one of the ways that we truly receive the king

169
00:15:25,000 --> 00:15:29,000
 is by first dethroning all of the others?

170
00:15:29,000 --> 00:15:32,000
 Come on, church.

171
00:15:32,000 --> 00:15:35,000
 Could it be that we are called to receive our king,

172
00:15:35,000 --> 00:15:44,000
 and yet first we must dethrone the other kings that still rule and reign within us?

173
00:15:44,000 --> 00:15:46,000
 This is the challenge that we're going to be bringing you every week

174
00:15:46,000 --> 00:15:49,000
 of our Advent series over the next four Sundays.

175
00:15:49,000 --> 00:15:53,000
 We're actually going to take a look at a different character in the Advent story

176
00:15:53,000 --> 00:15:56,000
 and show their perspective, and from their perspective,

177
00:15:56,000 --> 00:16:01,000
 help us to see maybe some of those kings that we hold on to,

178
00:16:01,000 --> 00:16:07,000
 that causes us not to have that room for the true king to reign.

179
00:16:07,000 --> 00:16:08,000
 For here's the reality.

180
00:16:08,000 --> 00:16:20,000
 In order to enthrone Jesus in your life, you will first need to dethrone everything else.

181
00:16:20,000 --> 00:16:25,000
 Today, I want to start that journey with you by taking you to one of the characters

182
00:16:25,000 --> 00:16:28,000
 of the Christmas story that we don't talk about very often.

183
00:16:28,000 --> 00:16:31,000
 One of the characters that actually has a prominent place in the story,

184
00:16:31,000 --> 00:16:36,000
 but is kind of in the background as Matthew presents it to us.

185
00:16:36,000 --> 00:16:39,000
 But when we see this character and we understand them,

186
00:16:39,000 --> 00:16:43,000
 it actually says some pretty deep things to what might be blocking

187
00:16:43,000 --> 00:16:48,000
 or occupying our hearts and stopping Jesus from being with us.

188
00:16:48,000 --> 00:16:52,000
 So I want to take us to Matthew, and I want to read to you a bit of his story,

189
00:16:52,000 --> 00:16:55,000
 his presentation of the birth of Jesus.

190
00:16:55,000 --> 00:16:59,000
 This is Matthew 2, starting in verse 1.

191
00:16:59,000 --> 00:17:05,000
 After Jesus was born in Bethlehem in Judea, during the time of King Herod,

192
00:17:05,000 --> 00:17:08,000
 Magi from the east came to Jerusalem and asked,

193
00:17:08,000 --> 00:17:12,000
 "Where is the one who has been born King of the Jews?

194
00:17:12,000 --> 00:17:16,000
 For we saw his star in the east, and we have come to worship him."

195
00:17:16,000 --> 00:17:23,000
 When King Herod heard this, he was disturbed, and all of Jerusalem with him.

196
00:17:23,000 --> 00:17:28,000
 When he called together all of the people's chief priests and the teachers of the law,

197
00:17:28,000 --> 00:17:32,000
 he asked them, "Where the Christ and the Messiah was to be born?"

198
00:17:32,000 --> 00:17:34,000
 "Oh, in Bethlehem in Judea," they replied,

199
00:17:34,000 --> 00:17:39,000
 "because this is what the prophet has written," and then they quote from Micah 5, verse 2.

200
00:17:39,000 --> 00:17:44,000
 "But you, Bethlehem, in the land of Judea, are by no means the least amongst the rulers of Judea.

201
00:17:44,000 --> 00:17:51,000
 For out of you will come a ruler who will be the shepherd of my people Israel."

202
00:17:51,000 --> 00:17:57,000
 Then Herod called the Magi secretly and found out from them the exact time when the star had appeared.

203
00:17:57,000 --> 00:17:59,000
 He sent them to Bethlehem, and he said this,

204
00:17:59,000 --> 00:18:01,000
 "Oh, go and make careful search for this child.

205
00:18:01,000 --> 00:18:06,000
 As soon as you find him, report to me so that I too may go and worship him."

206
00:18:06,000 --> 00:18:08,000
 Yeah, no.

207
00:18:08,000 --> 00:18:12,000
 After they had heard the king, they went on their way,

208
00:18:12,000 --> 00:18:16,000
 and the star that they had seen stopped over the place where the child was.

209
00:18:16,000 --> 00:18:19,000
 When they saw the star, they were overjoyed.

210
00:18:19,000 --> 00:18:22,000
 On coming to the house, they saw the child with his mother Mary,

211
00:18:22,000 --> 00:18:25,000
 and they bowed down and worshipped him.

212
00:18:25,000 --> 00:18:29,000
 Then they opened their treasures and presented him with gifts of gold and incense and myrrh.

213
00:18:29,000 --> 00:18:34,000
 And having been warned in a dream not to return to Herod,

214
00:18:34,000 --> 00:18:37,000
 they returned to their country by another route.

215
00:18:37,000 --> 00:18:39,000
 Jump down to verse 16.

216
00:18:39,000 --> 00:18:44,000
 "When Herod realized that he had been outwitted by the Magi, he was furious,

217
00:18:44,000 --> 00:18:50,000
 and he gave orders to kill all the boys in Bethlehem and its vicinity who were two years old and under.

218
00:18:50,000 --> 00:18:53,000
 In accordance with the time that he had learned from the Magi,

219
00:18:53,000 --> 00:18:56,000
 then what was said through the prophet Jeremiah was fulfilled.

220
00:18:56,000 --> 00:19:00,000
 A voice is heard in Ramah, weeping and great mourning,

221
00:19:00,000 --> 00:19:07,000
 Rachel weeping for her children and refusing to be comforted because they are no more."

222
00:19:07,000 --> 00:19:11,000
 This is not a Hallmark Christmas card special.

223
00:19:11,000 --> 00:19:15,000
 I mean, this story is pretty full on.

224
00:19:15,000 --> 00:19:19,000
 It's a story of power gone wrong.

225
00:19:19,000 --> 00:19:22,000
 It's a story of oppression and jealousy.

226
00:19:22,000 --> 00:19:28,000
 And it's the story of death right alongside of life.

227
00:19:28,000 --> 00:19:33,000
 And right in the center of this story is a character that Matthew introduced us to, King Herod.

228
00:19:33,000 --> 00:19:36,000
 Herod is not mentioned a lot in the New Testament,

229
00:19:36,000 --> 00:19:41,000
 but in this moment he takes a place within this story of the birth of Jesus.

230
00:19:41,000 --> 00:19:45,000
 History tells us some very important things about King Herod.

231
00:19:45,000 --> 00:19:47,000
 King Herod was a Gentile by background.

232
00:19:47,000 --> 00:19:51,000
 His mother was an Edomite and his father was an Arab.

233
00:19:51,000 --> 00:19:59,000
 But he, in about 40 BC, the Roman Senate decreed that he would become the ruler over Judea.

234
00:19:59,000 --> 00:20:04,000
 And actually this took place, he took power in 37 BC.

235
00:20:04,000 --> 00:20:09,000
 Now in 37 BC, he actually came into Jerusalem, took siege of the city,

236
00:20:09,000 --> 00:20:14,000
 used armies, killed many, took over power by violence.

237
00:20:14,000 --> 00:20:19,000
 And he established for himself a rule and a reign within these people.

238
00:20:19,000 --> 00:20:25,000
 History tells us that he was both a brilliant but a ruthless leader.

239
00:20:25,000 --> 00:20:30,000
 On one side, Herod brought a lot of prosperity to Judea in his reign.

240
00:20:30,000 --> 00:20:34,000
 He was really into building projects and he built many things in those days,

241
00:20:34,000 --> 00:20:39,000
 including actually the rebuilding of the temple that was lying there not fully rebuilt.

242
00:20:39,000 --> 00:20:45,000
 He rebuilt the temple so that the temple in Jesus' day was actually known as Herod's temple.

243
00:20:45,000 --> 00:20:51,000
 But he also rebuilt and built lots of other things around Jerusalem, aqueducts to bring waters to the various villages around it.

244
00:20:51,000 --> 00:20:56,000
 He actually brought a lot of prosperity to the city, but that prosperity came at a cost.

245
00:20:56,000 --> 00:21:03,000
 He was ruthless and he controlled his environment with a tight grip.

246
00:21:03,000 --> 00:21:08,000
 One of the things that history tells us about him is that he was a paranoid man when it came to power.

247
00:21:08,000 --> 00:21:13,000
 And he constantly thought that everybody around him was trying to take power from him.

248
00:21:13,000 --> 00:21:19,000
 And the last thing he wanted to do was to let go of control, let go of power, and lose his prestige.

249
00:21:19,000 --> 00:21:26,000
 This got so bad for Herod that he came to believe that his own family was trying to plot to overthrow him.

250
00:21:26,000 --> 00:21:34,000
 And history tells us that even though he loved his wife, he killed his wife, he killed her mother, his mother-in-law,

251
00:21:34,000 --> 00:21:42,000
 and then he ends up killing three of his sons because he thinks they're going to overthrow his power.

252
00:21:42,000 --> 00:21:47,000
 This leads to Caesar Augustus writing in one of his writings quite a little funny quote.

253
00:21:47,000 --> 00:21:55,000
 He says this, he says, "It would be better to be one of Herod's pigs than one of his sons."

254
00:21:55,000 --> 00:21:59,000
 But alongside of this comes the reason why he was so ruthless and paranoid.

255
00:21:59,000 --> 00:22:06,000
 His whole identity was built on this phrase, "I am the king of the Jews."

256
00:22:06,000 --> 00:22:14,000
 In almost every correspondence that Herod sent out, he would sign it, "King of the Jews" or "King of Judea."

257
00:22:14,000 --> 00:22:18,000
 He made himself a de facto king over those people.

258
00:22:18,000 --> 00:22:28,000
 And he did that through the kind of bloody violence that we often see is taken place by those that have authoritarian rule over the people under them.

259
00:22:28,000 --> 00:22:32,000
 And Herod really pitches that for us in a bloody, horrible way.

260
00:22:32,000 --> 00:22:37,000
 And as Matthew describes this person and brings him into the biblical story of Jesus' birth,

261
00:22:37,000 --> 00:22:43,000
 this is the background he's bringing to us, this idea of his paranoia, of his jealousy,

262
00:22:43,000 --> 00:22:48,000
 and of his desire to squash all attempts at taking power from him.

263
00:22:48,000 --> 00:22:54,000
 So he actually says right at the start, when the Magi show up, they say this word.

264
00:22:54,000 --> 00:22:58,000
 They say, "Where is the one who has been born?" Notice this, "King of the Jews."

265
00:22:58,000 --> 00:23:04,000
 Can you imagine how offensive that would be to Herod, who self-titled himself the "King of the Jews"?

266
00:23:04,000 --> 00:23:12,000
 Now these Magi are saying, "There are people in Judea who are saying that there is another one that's been born who holds this title, 'King of the Jews.'"

267
00:23:12,000 --> 00:23:18,000
 It says in verse 3, "When King Herod heard this, he was disturbed."

268
00:23:18,000 --> 00:23:25,000
 The Greek word there means literally, "Filled with violent anger and pain from within."

269
00:23:25,000 --> 00:23:33,000
 This totally wrecked his world from within because this was suddenly a threat to his power.

270
00:23:33,000 --> 00:23:40,000
 And so he tells the Magi, he finds out from the chief priests and the rulers of the law where this Messiah would be born,

271
00:23:40,000 --> 00:23:42,000
 Bethlehem, they say, quoting Micah 5.2.

272
00:23:42,000 --> 00:23:50,000
 He then pulls the Magi together and he says, "Look, go find him. Let me know because I want to go and offer my worship to him as well."

273
00:23:50,000 --> 00:23:56,000
 And the Magi have no idea that actually Herod has this anger and this violence within him.

274
00:23:56,000 --> 00:23:58,000
 They don't know that he wants to harm the child.

275
00:23:58,000 --> 00:24:01,000
 So they go off thinking that they're going to do what the king has asked them to do.

276
00:24:01,000 --> 00:24:05,000
 But God steps in as God has done every step of the way.

277
00:24:05,000 --> 00:24:11,000
 And God brings a dream to the Magi and says, "Don't go back to Herod for he only wants bad for this child.

278
00:24:11,000 --> 00:24:14,000
 You need to return to your country another way."

279
00:24:14,000 --> 00:24:25,000
 When Herod finds out about this, notice the word it says. It says, "He was furious," which in the Greek means furious.

280
00:24:25,000 --> 00:24:35,000
 He was so angry that this has happened that he decides to do one of the most horrible things that are recorded for us in the whole of the New Testament.

281
00:24:35,000 --> 00:24:48,000
 His anger and his jealousy and the threat to his power is so overwhelming for him that he actually asks for his subjects to kill the children of Bethlehem and its vicinity.

282
00:24:48,000 --> 00:24:51,000
 Anyone under the age of two years old to be put to death.

283
00:24:51,000 --> 00:24:55,000
 And there is this thing that history has called the massacre of innocence.

284
00:24:55,000 --> 00:24:58,000
 And this massacre actually took place.

285
00:24:58,000 --> 00:25:04,000
 This is true, real history that those under the age of two in Bethlehem were killed.

286
00:25:04,000 --> 00:25:09,000
 And I want you to see what's happening here in our Christmas birth Jesus story.

287
00:25:09,000 --> 00:25:19,000
 That when God steps into the world with this incredible moment where He brings hope and life in the presence of Jesus, notice what happens.

288
00:25:19,000 --> 00:25:26,000
 Immediately there is a battle. There is a fight back from sin and evil and brokenness.

289
00:25:26,000 --> 00:25:36,000
 And so right at the beginning of Jesus' story, you have the hope of God in the person of Christ and you have evil fighting back with death.

290
00:25:36,000 --> 00:25:41,000
 And life and death sit side by side.

291
00:25:41,000 --> 00:25:45,000
 Worship and weeping happen in Rama and Bethlehem.

292
00:25:45,000 --> 00:25:57,000
 And what happens with Herod is really just the beginning of everything that is going to take place that will ultimately lead Jesus to death on a Roman cross.

293
00:25:57,000 --> 00:26:05,000
 That there is a spiritual battle at work in this world between the goodness of God and the evil that is present here.

294
00:26:05,000 --> 00:26:20,000
 And what we see in this character of Herod is the worst of what evil does when it is given control and power in human ways.

295
00:26:20,000 --> 00:26:28,000
 And when we sit and we realize all of this, we come to realize that that battle between good and evil,

296
00:26:28,000 --> 00:26:35,000
 it's not just at war in the world around us, but if we're honest, it's at war within us too.

297
00:26:35,000 --> 00:26:40,000
 If we're honest about it, we would recognize that although it might look different for every single person in this room,

298
00:26:40,000 --> 00:26:45,000
 all of us have to wrestle with a spirit of Herod within us.

299
00:26:45,000 --> 00:26:51,000
 In the sin in which we grapple with and in the evil that is present in this world,

300
00:26:51,000 --> 00:27:00,000
 many of us can recognize that what we see in Herod we can sometimes unfortunately see in ourselves.

301
00:27:00,000 --> 00:27:13,000
 Matthew paints a picture for us of a man who cannot make room for Jesus because of the threat Jesus was to his own power, his own control, and his own prestige.

302
00:27:13,000 --> 00:27:19,000
 And as much as we probably don't want to think about it, and to be honest, we'd look at a character like Herod and say,

303
00:27:19,000 --> 00:27:22,000
 "Well, I would never want to be like that."

304
00:27:22,000 --> 00:27:33,000
 I think the reality is for all of us that we struggle to some degree with maybe not always wanting to make room, more room for Jesus.

305
00:27:33,000 --> 00:27:44,000
 Because we recognize in order to do so, we would have to submit a little bit more of our power, of our control, and our prestige.

306
00:27:44,000 --> 00:27:50,000
 And when we sit in that reality, we soberly come to think of discipleship like this,

307
00:27:50,000 --> 00:27:57,000
 that maybe we do want more of Jesus, but we recognize the submission that it will require.

308
00:27:57,000 --> 00:28:01,000
 We recognize the sin that it will need for us to deal with.

309
00:28:01,000 --> 00:28:05,000
 We recognize those broken parts of our personality that we might finally need to address.

310
00:28:05,000 --> 00:28:14,000
 And when we see that, we count the cost, and we decide that Jesus is happy in the stable.

311
00:28:14,000 --> 00:28:21,000
 See, we have to recognize that it's easy to have a Savior, but it's a lot harder to have a Lord.

312
00:28:21,000 --> 00:28:30,000
 Jesus died on the cross so that you wouldn't just know a Savior, but that you would also have a Lord, that you would have a King that you submit yourself to.

313
00:28:30,000 --> 00:28:39,000
 You know, salvation is easy, but discipleship requires framing through obedience.

314
00:28:39,000 --> 00:28:54,000
 And obedience will require a cost, will come with your choices, will come with the decisions that you'll make to sacrifice and lay down and remove and to repent and to come before the Lord in the many ways you...

315
00:28:54,000 --> 00:29:00,000
 Discipleship is a process of obedience before the movement of the Holy Spirit in our lives.

316
00:29:00,000 --> 00:29:08,000
 But like Herod, we can desire to want to hold on to our power, hold on to our control, hold on to our prestige,

317
00:29:08,000 --> 00:29:15,000
 rather than lay those down, pick up the cross and truly follow Him.

318
00:29:15,000 --> 00:29:22,000
 When we wrestle with this, I think we come to realize something that's truly profound.

319
00:29:22,000 --> 00:29:30,000
 That it's really hard to make room for a King when you currently see yourself as one.

320
00:29:30,000 --> 00:29:32,000
 Come on, church.

321
00:29:32,000 --> 00:29:39,000
 It's really hard to make room for a King when you currently see yourself as one.

322
00:29:39,000 --> 00:29:48,000
 Could it be that the first King that needs to be laid down by all of us is actually ourselves?

323
00:29:48,000 --> 00:29:56,000
 And in discipleship, I recognize that the Lord is not done with me yet, but I need to be done with me.

324
00:29:56,000 --> 00:30:01,000
 I need to be done with my selfish ambition and pride.

325
00:30:01,000 --> 00:30:08,000
 I need to be done with the fact that I like power and power can be quite seductive in my life.

326
00:30:08,000 --> 00:30:14,000
 I need to be done with the reality that I do like to control as a leader at times.

327
00:30:14,000 --> 00:30:20,000
 And sometimes it's easier to control others than to submit to their wills.

328
00:30:20,000 --> 00:30:28,000
 I have to wrestle deeply with myself personally for some of the Herod thinking and living that I know is at work within me.

329
00:30:28,000 --> 00:30:37,000
 And I wonder whether that might be not an easy but honest invitation for you at the start of Advent in 2025.

330
00:30:37,000 --> 00:30:42,000
 Could be the King that you need to lay down is actually yourself.

331
00:30:42,000 --> 00:30:50,000
 You will never be able to make more room for Jesus when you are the King that you're currently worshiping.

332
00:30:50,000 --> 00:30:59,000
 Come on church, you're never going to make more room for Jesus when you're the King that you're currently worshiping.

333
00:30:59,000 --> 00:31:06,000
 This is why I love what Matthew does in the presentation here because he doesn't just show us Herod, but he also shows us the Magi.

334
00:31:06,000 --> 00:31:13,000
 Now the Magi are fascinating because the Magi are also people of power, control, and prestige.

335
00:31:13,000 --> 00:31:22,000
 And I think what Matthew does so beautifully and subtly here is he compares Herod's reaction to the birth of Jesus to the Magi's reaction.

336
00:31:22,000 --> 00:31:26,000
 Because like Herod, the Magi's were powerful.

337
00:31:26,000 --> 00:31:31,000
 People all around the land looked to them for direction and guidance and leadership.

338
00:31:31,000 --> 00:31:40,000
 Like Herod, he had control over his people, so the Magi had great control over the people that submitted themselves to them.

339
00:31:40,000 --> 00:31:49,000
 But unlike Herod, the Magi realized that in the birth of Jesus, this King of the Jews, that a new power has entered this world.

340
00:31:49,000 --> 00:31:56,000
 A power whereby every previous pretense to power must now bow down.

341
00:31:56,000 --> 00:32:05,000
 And so these Magi, at a great cost to themselves, to their reputation, to their grip on power, to their control,

342
00:32:05,000 --> 00:32:15,000
 travel from a faraway land, follow the star, bring these gifts, lay them down before Jesus, and worship Him.

343
00:32:15,000 --> 00:32:30,000
 The Magi reveal to us that even when we have power, control, and prestige, the only right response, if we want to make more room for Jesus, is to lay those things down.

344
00:32:30,000 --> 00:32:32,000
 That's the journey for all of us.

345
00:32:32,000 --> 00:32:38,000
 For some of us, that journey will feel like the Magi journey. It'll feel like a long, long way to go.

346
00:32:38,000 --> 00:32:41,000
 For others of us, it might feel like a simple step.

347
00:32:41,000 --> 00:32:47,000
 But if you really want to make more room for Jesus, here in 2025, here's simply how you do it.

348
00:32:47,000 --> 00:32:58,000
 You take the greatest gift that you have, yourself, you bring it to the feet of Jesus, and you lay it down.

349
00:32:58,000 --> 00:33:05,000
 When you do that, Jesus' reign and authority and kingship is found.

350
00:33:05,000 --> 00:33:20,000
 When we understand that in laying down of our power is the only way to receive the power that reigns for eternity, we become more like the Magi than Herod.

351
00:33:20,000 --> 00:33:27,000
 And I pray that as we enter into this time together over the next number of weeks, the starting point would be,

352
00:33:27,000 --> 00:33:38,000
 "Lord, where is it where I am ruling and reigning in such a way over my life that you are still living in the stable?"

353
00:33:38,000 --> 00:33:42,000
 I want to make room. I want to change.

354
00:33:42,000 --> 00:33:49,000
 So Lord, let me dethrone myself so that you may be enthroned.

355
00:33:49,000 --> 00:33:55,000
 Can I pray for you? Let's pray.

356
00:33:55,000 --> 00:34:00,000
 Father, what a precious thing the Advent story and Christmas is.

357
00:34:00,000 --> 00:34:11,000
 This one singular candle of hope in the birth of Jesus, where every power now submits to and is laid down before.

358
00:34:11,000 --> 00:34:22,000
 But Lord, we recognize that we can be a little bit like Herod at times, wanting to control our lives, be masters of our own futures.

359
00:34:22,000 --> 00:34:29,000
 That we might have a Savior in you, but we struggle at times to be submitted to our Lord.

360
00:34:29,000 --> 00:34:35,000
 Father, I want to pray for anyone here today where this message has really struck a chord with them.

361
00:34:35,000 --> 00:34:43,000
 Maybe they know in some areas of their lives or their heart that they have not made room for you, but only made room for themselves.

362
00:34:43,000 --> 00:34:46,000
 Lord, I recognize that in my heart.

363
00:34:46,000 --> 00:34:55,000
 Lord, would you forgive me? And would you forgive those of us in this room watching online and the overflow where that resonates for us?

364
00:34:55,000 --> 00:35:04,000
 And maybe just take a time, take a moment right now, if that is your journey, just to bring it to the Lord in confession.

365
00:35:04,000 --> 00:35:08,000
 It's just a beautiful thing. It's just a way of saying, "Lord, would you forgive me?"

366
00:35:08,000 --> 00:35:17,000
 Where I recognize that at times I make myself king and therefore fail to make you Lord.

367
00:35:17,000 --> 00:35:23,000
 Would you forgive me?

368
00:35:23,000 --> 00:35:26,000
 And Fathers, we make more room for you.

369
00:35:26,000 --> 00:35:33,000
 What a joy it will be to know the eternal power that comes from your Spirit at work in us.

370
00:35:33,000 --> 00:35:40,000
 That that same Spirit that raised Jesus from the dead is and will be and can be ever more and more and more within us.

371
00:35:40,000 --> 00:35:44,000
 So Lord, I want to pray for my brothers and sisters here.

372
00:35:44,000 --> 00:35:48,000
 Lord, that Advent this year would be a joyous time.

373
00:35:48,000 --> 00:35:53,000
 Where they would come under the authority and the kingship and the power of Jesus like never before.

374
00:35:53,000 --> 00:35:58,000
 And that out of that power they would find themselves alive like never before.

375
00:35:58,000 --> 00:36:06,000
 The very people that you have created them to be and like in Ephesians 4, attaining to the whole measure of the wholeness of Christ.

376
00:36:06,000 --> 00:36:09,000
 We thank you Lord that that is not just words on a page.

377
00:36:09,000 --> 00:36:12,000
 It is a promise that we take to you in prayer.

378
00:36:12,000 --> 00:36:16,000
 Lord, more of you and less of us.

379
00:36:16,000 --> 00:36:18,000
 And we pray this in Jesus' name.

380
00:36:18,000 --> 00:36:20,000
 Everyone says, "Amen."

381
00:36:20,000 --> 00:36:27,000
 Amen. Would you stand with me and we're going to respond together in a final time of just worship here this morning.

382
00:36:28,000 --> 00:36:33,000
 [Music]

